{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522421"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13829"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13829"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.7,0.23,0.02,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6446"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49816"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6446","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6446"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13829"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2157"},{"type":"tags","id":"2776"},{"type":"tags","id":"9042"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12745"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16416"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49816"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old farmer presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of excessive tearing and blepharospasm on his left eye. He has had a dacryoma present on his left eye for five years for which he declined surgical management. He also has had dry eyes for ten years without investigation, had squamous cell carcinoma removed from his lower leg two years prior, and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His visual acuity and visual fields are not affected, and there is no photophobia. There is a soft, non-tender swelling below the medial canthus of the left eye (Image). Gentle pressure on this swelling causes reflux of mucopurulent material through the punctum. There were adherent strands on the cornea seen on the slit lamp examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnose is the most likely cause of his new symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dacryocystitis","Filamentary keratitis","Bacterial conjunctivitis","Herpes simplex keratitis","Corneal abrasion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis causing this patient\u0027s new symptoms of excessive tearing and blepharospasm is \u003Cstrong\u003Efilamentary keratitis\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterized by mucus strands adhering to the corneal surface, which were observed on slit lamp examination. Filamentary keratitis is often associated with dry eye syndrome, which this patient has had for 10 years. The symptoms of excessive tearing (paradoxically occurring in dry eye) and blepharospasm are consistent with this diagnosis.  He may also present with photophobia though it was absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocystitis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to an infection of the lacrimal sac. While the patient has a long-standing dacryoma (a benign lacrimal sac mucocele), the description of a soft, non-tender swelling suggests that it is not currently infected. Dacryocystitis typically presents with pain, redness, and swelling in the inner corner of the eye, which are not described here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with redness, discharge, and a gritty sensation in the eye. Patients often give a history of sticky eyes in the morning as well.  While there is mention of mucopurulent material from the lacrimal sac, there are no signs of conjunctival inflammation described, making this diagnosis less likely.  It is unlikely to have presented as well with a two-month history of symptoms - bacterial conjunctivitis typically resolves within one-week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex keratitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with pain, photophobia, and often a characteristic dendritic ulcer on the cornea. The absence of photophobia and the presence of corneal strands rather than a dendritic ulcer make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorneal abrasion\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes acute pain, tearing, and often photophobia. While it can cause a foreign body sensation, it would not explain the adherent strands seen on the cornea. The chronic nature of the symptoms also makes this acute condition less likely.  Filamentary keratitis may occur secondary to significant corneal abrasion as injury to the eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s long-standing dry eye condition, combined with the presence of adherent strands on the cornea and symptoms of excessive tearing and blepharospasm, strongly point to filamentary keratitis as the most likely cause of his new symptoms. Management would involve addressing the underlying dry eye condition and removing the corneal filaments to provide symptomatic relief.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Filamentary keratitis is characterised by mucus strands adhering to the corneal surface, often associated with dry eye syndrome.","Dacryoma (lacrimal sac mucocele) is a complication of chronic nasolacrimal duct obstruction.","Treatment of filamentary keratitis involves addressing the underlying cause and removing the filaments."],"references":["Mannis T, Bernfeld E. Filamentary Keratis. In: Eye Wiki [online]. 2023. Available at: https://eyewiki.aao.org/Filamentary_Keratitis","Tanioka H, Yokoi N, Komuro A, Shimamoto T, Kawasaki S, Matsuda A, et al. Investigation of the Corneal Filament in Filamentary Keratitis. Investigative Opthalmology and Visual Science. 2009;50:3696-3702. Available at: https://iovs.arvojournals.org/article.aspx?articleid=2185853","Ozgonul C, Uysal Y, Ayyildiz O, Kucukevcilioglu M. Clinical features and management of dacryops. The International Journal on Orbital Disorders, Oculoplastic and Lacrimal Surgery. 2018;37(4). Available at: https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01676830.2017.1423081"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13829"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20776"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20776","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20776"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sfHToZ9UXKGtP5TrOyQH2BdCecAYJB.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/sfHToZ9UXKGtP5TrOyQH2BdCecAYJB.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T19:41:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T13:07:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6446"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49816"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self"